5|$|The third spirit, <b>the</b> <b>Ghost</b> of Christmas Yet to Come, shows Scrooge a Christmas Day in the future. <b>The</b> <b>ghost</b> {{shows him}} scenes {{involving}} {{the death of}} a disliked man. The man's funeral will only be attended by local businessmen if lunch is provided. His charwoman, his laundress, and the local undertaker steal some of his possessions and sell them to a fence. When Scrooge asks <b>the</b> <b>ghost</b> to show anyone who feels any emotion over the man's death, <b>the</b> <b>ghost</b> can only show him the pleasure of a poor couple in debt to the man, rejoicing that his death gives them more time to put their finances in order. After Scrooge asks to see some tenderness connected with any death, <b>the</b> <b>ghost</b> shows him Bob Cratchit and his family mourning the passing of Tiny Tim. <b>The</b> <b>ghost</b> then shows Scrooge the man's neglected grave, whose tombstone bears Scrooge's name. Sobbing, Scrooge pledges to <b>the</b> <b>ghost</b> that he will change his ways to avoid this outcome.|$|E
